TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Study Of Organization Performance For Experimental Structures Of Two, Three and Four Levels
AU  - Jones, Halsey R.
Y1  - 1969/09/01
PY  - 1969
DA  - 1969/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255182
DO  - 10.5465/255182
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 351
EP  - 365
VL  - 12
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The purpose of this research was to investigate the effects of organization levels upon organization performance. The methodology involved the establishment of experimental organizations of four, three, and two levels, and these were evaluated in terms of profitability, communication speed and accuracy, and individual member attitudes. The results of the experiment provide support for the hypothesis that the number of levels in an organization will affect organization performance. It provided limited support for the hypothesis that the fewer the number of levels the better the performance.
AB  - The purpose of this research was to investigate the effects of organization levels upon organization performance. The methodology involved the establishment of experimental organizations of four, three, and two levels, and these were evaluated in terms of profitability, communication speed and accuracy, and individual member attitudes. The results of the experiment provide support for the hypothesis that the number of levels in an organization will affect organization performance. It provided limited support for the hypothesis that the fewer the number of levels the better the performance.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255182
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255182
Y2  - 2026/04/24
